"Barbraud C., Weimerskirch H.","Antarctic birds breed later in response to climate change",2006,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","103","16",,"6248","6251",,,10.1073/pnas.0510397103,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646553072&partnerID=40&md5=ec12a54c614fec0c593d4b6d68d8009a","Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Unité Propre de Recherche 1934, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, 79360 Villiers en Bois, France","Barbraud, C., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Unité Propre de Recherche 1934, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, 79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Weimerskirch, H., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Unité Propre de Recherche 1934, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, 79360 Villiers en Bois, France","In the northern hemisphere, there is compelling evidence for climate-related advances of spring events, but no such long-term biological time series exist for the southern hemisphere. We have studied a unique data set of dates of first arrival and laying of first eggs over a 55-year period for the entire community of Antarctic seabirds in East Antarctica. The records over this long period show a general unexpected tendency toward later arrival and laying, an inverse trend to those observed in the northern hemisphere. Overall, species now arrive at their colonies 9.1 days later, on average, and lay eggs an average of 2.1 days later than in the early 1950s. Furthermore, these delays are linked to a decrease in sea ice extent that has occurred in eastern Antarctica, which underlies the contrasted effects of global climate change on species in Antarctica. © 2006 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Antarctica; Phenology; Sea ice; Seabirds","Antarctica; article; bird; breeding; climate change; egg laying; nonhuman; priority journal; sea ice; spring; Animal Migration; Animals; Antarctic Regions; Birds; Breeding; Climate; Aves",,,,,,"Beebee, T.J.C., (1995) Nature, 374, pp. 219-220; Crick, H.Q.P., Dudley, C., Glue, D.E., Thomson, D.L., (1997) Nature, 388, p. 526; Walther, G.R., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Beebee, T.J.C., Fremont, J.-M., Bairlein, F., (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 389-395; Parmesan, C., Yohe, G., (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 37-42; Root, T.L., Price, J.T., Hall, K.R., Schneider, S.H., Rosenzweig, C., Pounds, A.J., (2003) Nature, 421, pp. 57-60; (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, , Houghton, J. T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D. J., Noguer, M., van der Linden, P. J. & Xiaosu, D., eds. (Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U.K.); Ridoux, V., Offredo, C., (1989) Polar Biol., 9, pp. 137-145; Liu, J., Yuan, X., Rind, D., Martinson, D.G., (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29, pp. 24-30; Thompson, D.W.V., Solomon, S., (2002) Science, 296, pp. 895-899; Nicol, S., Pauly, T., Bindoff, N.L., Wright, S., Thiele, D., Hosie, G.W., Strutton, P.G., Woehler, E., (2000) Nature, 406, pp. 504-507; Loeb, V., Siegel, V., Holm-Hansen, O., Hewitt, R., Fraser, W., Trivelpiece, W., Trivelpiece, S., (1997) Nature, 387, pp. 897-900; Croxall, J.P., Trathan, P.N., Murphy, E.J., (2002) Science, 297, pp. 1510-1514; Curran, M.A.J., Van Ommen, T.D., Morgan, V.I., Phillips, K.L., Palmer, A.S., (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1203-1206; Vaughan, D.G., Marshall, G.J., Connolley, W.M., King, J.C., Mulnavey, R., (2001) Science, 293, pp. 1777-1779; Atkinson, A., Siegel, V., Pakhomov, E., Rothery, P., (2004) Nature, 432, pp. 100-103; Parkinson, C.L., (2002) Ann. Glaciol., 34, pp. 435-440; Parkinson, C.L., (2004) Antarct. Sci., 16, pp. 387-400; Gaston, A.J., Hipfner, M., (1998) Can. J. Zool., 76, pp. 480-492; Ainley, D.G., (2002) The Adélie Penguin: Bellwether of Climate Change, , Columbia Univ. Press, New York; Chastel, O., Weimerskirch, H., Jouventin, P., (1995) Ecology, 76, pp. 2240-2246; Buse, A., Dury, S.J., Woodburn, R.J.W., Perrins, C.M., Good, J.E.G., (1999) Funct. Ecol., 13 (SUPPL. 1), pp. 74-82; Barbraud, C., Weimerskirch, H., (200